Influencer Semantic Similarity Analysis

Project Overview
This project analyzes the semantic similarity between influencer organic (non-sponsored) content, original sponsored posts, and AI-generated sponsored posts. The goal is to provide quantitative and statistical evidence that AI-generated sponsored content matches the influencer’s natural tone better than the original sponsored content.

Total Data Points
Organic Posts: ~5900 (organic_data.csv)
Training Posts: ~6100 (training_data.csv)
Top Influencer Pairs Analyzed: 10
Sponsored Posts per Influencer (Sample): ~10

Technical Workflow

1. Data Preparation
Used datasets: organic_data.csv, training_data.csv, and top5_influencers.csv (with organic, original sponsored, and AI-modified sponsored posts).

2. Script Development
Developed scripts: analyze_semantic_similarity.py, influencer_semantic_similarity.py, and semantic_similarity_analysis.py for similarity analysis and statistical testing.

3. Embedding Generation
Used the sentence-transformers library with the all-mpnet-base-v2 model to generate sentence embeddings for all posts.

4. Post-Neighbourhood (PN) Distance Calculation
For each sponsored post, cosine distances were calculated to all organic posts.
The 5 nearest neighbors were selected and the average PN distance was computed.

Two lists were created:
Original PN Distances
Modified PN Distances

5. Statistical Testing
Performed a paired t-test between the two PN distance lists.
Calculated mean original distance, mean modified distance, t-statistic, and p-value.

RAGs Design

Green:
AI-modified sponsored content is significantly closer to organic tone.
Lower PN distance and p-value < 0.05.

Amber:
Moderate improvement but not statistically significant.

Red:
No improvement or original sponsored content is closer.
 

Output and Statistical Results
Number of influencer pairs analyzed: 10
Mean Original Distance: 0.4746
Mean Modified Distance: 0.4396
T-statistic: 11.2881
p-value: 0.0001
Improvement Ratio: 
Improvement = (0.4746 - 0.4396) / 0.4746
Improvement ≈ 7.4%

Interpretation
Modified (AI-generated) sponsored content is statistically significantly closer to the influencer’s organic tone than the original sponsored content.

Conclusion

This project evaluated the semantic similarity between influencer organic posts, original sponsored posts, and AI-generated sponsored posts using sentence embeddings and Post-Neighbourhood (PN) distance analysis.
The results show that the mean PN distance for AI-generated sponsored posts (0.4396) is lower than that of original sponsored posts (0.4746), indicating that AI-generated content is semantically closer to the influencer’s organic writing style.
The paired t-test produced a very small p-value (< 0.0001), confirming that the improvement in similarity is statistically significant and not due to random variation.
Therefore, the analysis provides quantitative evidence that AI-generated sponsored content can better replicate an influencer’s natural tone and style compared to original sponsored posts.
This suggests that AI-assisted content generation can be an effective tool for producing sponsored posts that align more closely with an influencer’s authentic voice.



